{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619801"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16579"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60292"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1311"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1763"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21966"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA lumbar puncture can have both diagnostic and therapeutic. It is important to know when it is unsafe to perform this procedure\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions would lumbar puncture be both safe and therapeutically beneficial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brain abscess","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Posterior fossa tumour","Acute traumatic brain injury","Acute bacterial meningitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELumbar puncture (LP) safety depends on the absence of raised intracranial pressure that could lead to herniation. The clinical scenario describes a patient with likely idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH), where therapeutic LP can be both safe and beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E presents with headache and papilloedema, typically in young overweight women. After excluding other causes with imaging, LP not only confirms the diagnosis but can also provide symptomatic relief by reducing CSF pressure. Regular therapeutic LPs may be needed until definitive treatment is established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is an absolute contraindication to LP due to the risk of brain herniation from raised intracranial pressure and the potential for spreading infection along the neuraxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior fossa tumour\u003C/strong\u003E presents a significant risk of tonsillar herniation with LP due to the mass effect and associated raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute traumatic brain injury\u003C/strong\u003E commonly causes raised intracranial pressure and may have associated skull fractures or coagulopathy, making LP both dangerous and unnecessary for management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute bacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E with signs of raised intracranial pressure (such as papilloedema) requires brain imaging before LP is considered. If imaging shows features of raised ICP, LP should be deferred and empiric antibiotics started immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lumbar puncture is contraindicated in cases of raised intracranial pressure due to risk of brain herniation.","Lumbar puncture can be therapeutic in conditions causing increased CSF production such as pseudotumour cerebri.","Brain imaging should be performed prior to lumbar puncture if there are focal neurological signs, papilloedema, or altered consciousness."],"references":["Schmidt B, Czosnyka M, Cardim D, Czosnyka Z, Rosengarten B. Is Lumbar Puncture Needed? - Noninvasive Assessment of ICP Facilitates Decision Making in Patients with Suspected Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension. Ultraschall Med. 2023 Apr;44(2):e91-e98. doi: 10.1055/a-1586-6487. Epub 2021 Sep 8. PMID: 34496407; PMCID: PMC10063336.","Jane LA, Wray AA. Lumbar Puncture. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491485.","Kaya Tutar N, Kale N. The Relationship between Lumbar Puncture Opening Pressure and Retinal Nerve Fiber Layer Thickness in the Diagnosis of Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension: Is a Lumbar Puncture Always Necessary? Neurologist. 2024 Mar 1;29(2):91-95. doi: 10.1097/NRL.0000000000000528. PMID: 37839079."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60292"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16579"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60292"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T11:20:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:01:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"